 AMERICAN IMPERIALISM: MANIFEST DESTINY IN WESTERN MOVIES -- t17 THE TOWN AND THE CITY: SPACE AS THEME, PLACE AS CHARACTER -- t18 GLORY IN THE (WILD)FLOWER: ROMANTICISM ON THE OPEN RANGE -- t19 HEARTS OF DARKNESS, SOULS OF LIGHT: VISIONS OF NATURE IN AMERICAN FILM AND FICTION -- t20 A CHAPEL IN THE CANYON: RELIGIOSITY, AMERICAN-STYLE -- t21 MULTICULTURALISM, MORMONISM, AND MOVIES: HOLLYWOOD’S HISTORY AND CULTURAL APPROPRIATION -- t22 END OF THE TRAIL: THE DARK SIDE OF FAITH -- t23 RIDE OUT FOR VENGEANCE: REVISING A WESTERN PARADIGM -- t24 OLD TESTAMENT AND NEW: DAYS OF WRATH, ANGELS OF MERCY -- t25 THE CHURCH AND THE SALOON: CATHOLIC VERSUS PROTESTANT WESTERNS -- t26 ONWARD, CHRISTIAN SOLDIERS: THE PISTOL AND THE PULPIT -- t27 HARTS OF THE WEST: THE GOSPEL ACCORDING TO CLINT -- t28 THEN CAME SAM! FROM PAPPY TO PECKINPAH -- t29 COUNT NO MAN LUCKY UNTIL HIS DEATH: THE WESTERN AS AMERICAN TRAGEDY -- t30 BORN AGAIN: OF COWBOYS, CHRISTIANITY, AND CONVERSION -- tCONCLUSION. NO COUNTRY FOR BOLD MEN: THE WESTERN FILM IN THE TWENTY-FIRST CENTURY -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX OF FILMS AND SHOWS -- tGENERAL INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile political liberals celebrated the end of “cowboy politics” with the election of Barack Obama to the presidency, political conservatives in the Tea Party and other like-minded groups still vociferously support “cowboy” values such as small government, low taxes, free-market capitalism, and the right to bear arms. Yet, as Douglas Brode argues in this paradigm-shifting book, these supposedly cowboy or “Old West” values hail not so much from the actual American frontier of the nineteenth century as from Hollywood’s portrayal of it in the twentieth century. And a close reading of Western films and TV shows reveals a much more complex picture than the romanticized, simplistic vision espoused by the conservative right. Examining dozens of Westerns, including Gunfight at the O.K. Corral, Red River, 3:10 to Yuma (old and new), The Wild Ones, High Noon, My Darling Clementine, The Alamo, and No Country for Old Men, Brode demonstrates that the genre (with notable exceptions that he fully covers) was the product of Hollywood liberals who used it to project a progressive agenda on issues such as gun control, environmental protection, respect for non-Christian belief systems, and community cohesion versus rugged individualism. Challenging us to rethink everything we thought we knew about the genre, Brode argues that the Western stands for precisely the opposite of what most people today—whether they love it or hate it—believe to be the essential premise of “the only truly, authentically, and uniquely American narrative form.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aPolitics in motion pictures. 0aReligion in motion pictures. 0aWestern filmsxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70902740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292745568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292745568/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK